    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the sock thing makes sense but what's the part about it being \"spooky\"? i keep seeing that term in my textbook. why did einstein call it that? it feels like there's something more to it than just a secret handshake.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the \"spooky action at a distance,\" as Einstein called it, because it defied his understanding of the universe. He couldn't wrap his head around the idea that two particles could be connected in such a way that the state of one could instantly affect the state of the other, without any physical interaction. It's like if you had a pair of enchanted goblins that could instantly teleport from one end of the world to the other, and when one goblin decided to wear a red hat, the other goblin would instantly change into a red hat too, even if they were on opposite sides of the globe. Einstein was skeptical, thinking there must be some hidden rule or force at play, but quantum mechanics showed that this \"spooky\" connection is real, and it doesn't require any goblin magic or secret handshakes. It's just how the universe works at the quantum level.",
      "source": "target",
