    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the goblin detour! Einstein was a brilliant physicist, and he was very much concerned with the completeness of the theory of quantum mechanics. He believed that there must be some underlying, hidden variables that determined the outcomes of quantum experiments, much like how a goblin might have a secret map that tells them where to find hidden treasure. He thought that if we could just discover these hidden variables, we could explain the \"spooky action at a distance\" without needing to accept that particles could instantly affect each other across vast distances. Einstein's quest for hidden variables was part of his broader quest to find a more complete and deterministic theory of physics, one that didn't rely on the mysterious and seemingly random nature of quantum mechanics. It wasn't until later experiments, like those by John Bell, that the idea of hidden variables was shown to be incompatible with the predictions of quantum mechanics, solidifying the strange and fascinating nature of quantum entanglement.",
